doc.ContractDescription: THIS PROPOSED STUDY FOCUSES ON INVESTIGATING THE USE OF AQUARIUS SEA SURFACE SALINITY (SSS) MEASUREMENTS FOR IMPROVED DETECTION AND QUANTIFICATION OF THE MARINE BRANCH OF THE GLOBAL WATER CYCLE (REFERRED TO AS THE OCEAN WATER CYCLE HEREAFTER). AS STATED IN THE REPORT OF THE US CLIVAR SALINITY WORKING GROUP (2007) AND REITERATED IN THE WORKSHOP REPORT OF SALINITY PROCESSES IN THE UPPER-OCEAN REGIONAL STUDY (SPURS; 2009), ##NO SINGLE ELEMENT OF THE CLIMATE SYSTEM HAS AS MUCH IMPACT ON SOCIETY AS THE WATER CYCLE, YET THE SEEMINGLY MOST IMPORTANT PARTS OF THIS CYCLE OCCUR OVER THE VAST AND UNDERSAMPLED OCEAN##. PRESENTLY, OCEAN EVAPORATION (E) AND PRECIPITATION (P) ARE ESTIMATED FROM VARIOUS CONVENTIONAL AND RADAR MEASUREMENTS OF AIR-SEA VARIABLES AND THEIR DERIVATIVES. DESPITE MANY IMPROVEMENTS MADE IN PAST DECADES IN REFINING THE ALGORITHMS AND IMPROVING INPUT DATA QUALITY, A FUNDAMENTAL TRUTH REMAINS THAT GRIDDED E AND P PRODUCTS HAVE LARGE UNCERTAINTIES AND THERE ARE NO SUFFICIENT GROUND-BASED OBSERVATIONS TO VALIDATE THEM. GIVEN THAT OCEAN SALINITY IS A SENSITIVE INDICATOR OF THE CHANGE OF THE FRESHWATER FLUX (NAMELY, E-P) AT THE OCEAN SURFACE, USING THE OCEAN AS A SURROGATE OR RAIN GAUGE FOR THE GLOBAL WATER CYCLE HAS LONG BEEN PROPOSED. WITH THE UPCOMING LAUNCH OF AQUARIUS SSS MEASUREMENTS, THE TIME IS RIPE TO REVISIT THE CONCEPT OF OCEAN RAIN GAUGE AND TO DEFINE NEW STEPS TOWARDS ITS REALIZATION. THIS PROPOSED STUDY IS DEVOTED TO ADDRESS THIS ISSUE. THE CHALLENGE OF USING SALINITY INFORMATION TO EXTRACT E-P HAS BEEN RECOGNIZED. SSS AND E-P ARE RELATED THROUGH COMPLEX UPPER OCEAN DYNAMICS. UNLIKE SURFACE HEAT FLUX THAT SERVES AS BOTH FORCING AND DAMPING MECHANISMS FOR SST, E-P FORCES SSS ANOMALIES BUT DOES NOT DAMPEN THEM. SSS ANOMALIES TEND TO BE MORE PERSISTENT THAN SST, AND ARE MORE STRONGLY INFLUENCED BY OCEANIC ADVECTION/MIXING. THESE OCEANIC PROCESSES LEAD TO WEAK OR INSIGNIFICANT CORRELATION BETWEEN E-P AND SSS SEASONAL VARIABILITY IN MANY REGIONS. HOWEVER, THERE ARE TWO REGIONS WHERE E-P SHOWS A PREDOMINANT INFLUENCE ON SEASONAL SSS VARIABILITY: THE TROPICAL CONVERGENCE ZONES FEATURING HEAVY RAINFALL AND THE WESTERN NORTH PACIFIC FEATURING HIGH EVAPORATION. THE LARGE CONTRAST IN THE E-P/SSS CORRELATION AT DIFFERENT REGIONS LEADS TO THE FORMULATION OF A TWO-STEP STRATEGY FOR THE PROPOSED ACTIVITIES. SPECIFICALLY, WE CHOOSE THE REGIONS OF HIGH E-P/SSS CORRELATION AS A STARTING POINT TO OPTIMIZE THE USAGE OF AQUARIUS MEASUREMENTS AND ENHANCE THE CONFIDENCE LEVEL OF THE SCIENTIFIC FINDINGS. WITH AN IMPROVED UNDERSTANDING OF THE E-P/SSS RELATIONSHIP OBTAINED IN THESE FOCUSED REGIONS, WE EXTEND THE STUDY TO EXAMINE HOW E-P, EVEN AS A SECONDARY FORCING MECHANISM, AFFECTS THE SSS IN REGIONS WHERE OCEANIC ADVECTION/MIXING DOMINATE. THE PREMISE AND CHALLENGES THEN BECOME TO SOLVE THESE PROBLEMS: (I) HOW DO E-P AND OCEANIC PROCESSES ACT AND INTERACT TO GIVE RISE TO OBSERVED SALINITY VARIABILITY? (II) HOW DO WE IDENTIFY THE REGIONS WHERE E-P IS THE DOMINANT FORCING FOR SSS VARIABILITY? (III) HOW ACCURATE E-P CAN BE EXTRACTED IN THESE FOCUSED REGIONS? AND (IV) HOW DO WE OPTIMALLY USE THE E-P INFORMATION DERIVED FROM AQUARIUS SSS MEASUREMENTS TO IMPROVE EXISTING E-P ESTIMATES? IN ADDRESSING THE ABOVE QUESTIONS, WE PROPOSE TO USE BOTH DATA ANALYSIS AND MODELING APPROACH AND TO INTEGRATE SPURS FIELD OBSERVATIONS. WE EXPECT THAT THE PROPOSED STUDY WILL LEAD TO: (I) AN IN-DEPTH UNDERSTANDING OF KEY PROCESSES THAT GOVERN THE CORRELATION BETWEEN SSS AND E-P; (II) A FRAMEWORK IN LINKING E-P TO AQUARIUS SSS MEASUREMENTS; (III) A PRACTICAL APPROACH OF USING OCEAN SALINITY TO IMPROVE EXISTING E-P ESTIMATES; AND (IV) A USEFUL FEEDBACK TO THE GLOBAL WATER CYCLE COMMUNITY.

WE PROPOSE TO QUANTIFY THE IMPACT OF AEROSOLS FROM COMBUSTION SOURCES ON GLOBAL ACTINIC FLUXES, PHOTOLYSIS RATES, AND THUS TROPOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY. IN PARTICULAR, WE WILL EXAMINE THE EFFECTS OF (1) ORGANIC CARBON AEROSOLS THAT STRONGLY ABSORB ULTRAVIOLET LIGHT, I.E. BROWN CARBON, AND (2) INTERNALLY MIXED AND SIZE-RESOLVED LIGHT ABSORBING CARBONACEOUS AEROSOLS. THIS WORK WILL IMPROVE THE REPRESENTATION OF AEROSOL ABSORPTION AND SCATTERING IN THE FAST-JX PHOTOLYSIS SCHEME USED IN THE THREE-DIMENSIONAL ATMOSPHERIC CHEMICAL TRANSPORT MODEL OF NASA GLOBAL MODELING INITIATIVE (GMI), AND THE CALCULATION OF PHOTOLYSIS RATES AND TROPOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY WITHIN THE GMI COMBO MODEL. WE WILL EXPAND FAST-JX TO ACCOMMODATE THE OPTICAL PROPERTIES OF SIZE- AND MIXING STATE-DEPENDENT AEROSOL MODELS INCLUDING THE MULTIMODE, TWO-MOMENT MIT AEROSOL MODEL AND THE SECTIONAL AEROSOL SIMULATION PROGRAM. WE WILL THEN EVALUATE THE PERFORMANCE OF IMPROVED FAST-JX VERSUS A HIGH SPECTRAL RESOLUTION MODEL IN THE PRESENCE OF COMBUSTION AEROSOLS. WE WILL CONSTRAIN OUR RADIATIVE TRANSFER SIMULATIONS USING IN-SITU OBSERVATIONS FROM THE NASA INTERCONTINENTAL CHEMICAL TRANSPORT EXPERIMENT (INTEX-B) AND THE ARCTIC RESEARCH OF THE COMPOSITION OF THE TROPOSPHERE FROM AIRCRAFT AND SATELLITES (ARCTAS) SUBORBITAL CAMPAIGNS. THE IMPROVED FAST-JX SCHEME, ALONG WITH THREE-DIMENSIONAL AEROSOL FIELDS GENERATED OFFLINE WITH THE MIT AEROSOL-CLIMATE MODEL, WILL THEN BE IMPLEMENTED INTO THE NASA GMI COMBO MODEL TO INVESTIGATE THE IMPACT OF COMBUSTION AEROSOLS ON GLOBAL ACTINIC FLUX AND PHOTOCHEMISTRY. WE WILL EVALUATE THE GMI COMBO MODEL RESULTS WITH THE IMPROVED PHOTOLYSIS SCHEME BY COMPARISONS WITH IN-SITU OBSERVATIONS OF ACTINIC FLUX, AEROSOL PROPERTIES, AND TRACE GASES FROM INTEX-B AND ARCTAS AS WELL AS WITH NASA SATELLITE RETRIEVALS OF TRACE GASES (E.G., O3, NO2, CO, HCHO) FROM THE OZONE MONITORING INSTRUMENT (OMI) AND THE TROPOSPHERIC EMISSION SPECTROMETER (TES). THE COMMON SOURCE OF COMBUSTION AEROSOLS AND MANY REACTIVE TRACE GASES EMITTED FROM ANTHROPOGENIC ACTIVITIES AND BIOMASS BURNING, INCLUDING NOX AND VOLATILE ORGANIC COMPOUNDS OR VOCS THAT ARE THE MAIN PRECURSORS OF TROPOSPHERIC O3, MAKES THE RESULTS OF THIS STUDY CRITICAL TO ATMOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY, AIR QUALITY, AND CLIMATE MODELING STUDIES. THIS WORK DIRECTLY RESPONDS TO RESEARCH AREA B OF NNH10ZDA001N, A.14 ATMOSPHERIC COMPOSITION, MODELING, ANALYSIS AND PREDICTION, WHICH ENCOURAGES STUDIES OF AEROSOL CHARACTERISTICS WITH RESPECT TO THEIR IMPACTS ON ACTINIC FLUXES AND TROPOSPHERIC CHEMICAL PROCESSES.

THE EQUIPMENT PURCHASE WILL HELP MEET THE FOLLOWING GOALS: EVALUATION OF BMP PERFORMANCE. THE PRIMARY GOAL OF THE MONITORING PROGRAM IS TO EVALUATE THE PERFORMANCE OF THE BIORETENTION CELLS FOR STORMWATER TREATMENT. ACHIEVING THIS GOAL REQUIRES THE CONSTRUCTION OF ACCURATE WATER AND MASS BALANCES AROUND EACH BIORETENTION CELL. THE VARIABILITY OF QUALITY AND QUANTITY OF STORMWATER INFLOW CREATES CHALLENGES WITH RESPECT TO CONSTRUCTING MASS BALANCES, AND THUS WE HAVE RECOMMENDED A SYSTEM WITH REDUNDANT MEASUREMENTS OF FLOW IN ORDER TO ASSURE ACCURATE MEASUREMENTS OF THE INFLOWS TO AND OUTFLOWS FROM THE BIORETENTION CELL. CHARACTERIZATION OF WATERSHED LOADS. AN ADDITIONAL GOAL OF THE MONITORING IS TO MEASURE THE LOAD OF NUTRIENTS AND OTHER NONPOINT-SOURCE POLLUTANTS FROM THE WATERSHEDS SERVED BY THE BMPS. THE BMPS ARE DESIGNED TO TREAT LOW TO MEDIUM FLOWS AND IT IS EXPECTED THAT STORMWATER WILL BYPASS THE CELLS DURING INTENSE STORMS. THUS, MEASUREMENTS OF THE WATERSHED LOAD WILL PUT IN CONTEXT THE CONTRIBUTION OF THE BMPS TO ADDRESSING NONPOINT-SOURCE POLLUTION FROM THE WATERSHED.
